{"cursor":"16150","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox writer \n| name = Nigel Hamilton image = Nigel Hamilton pic.jpg imagesize = 175px caption\n| = Nigel Hamilton in 2008 pseudonym = birth_date = birth_place = Alnmouth,\n| Northumberland death_date = death_place = occupation = Non-fiction author,\n| academic, broadcaster nationality = British period = 1968–present genre\n| = biography, art of life writing, Military History, American presidency,\n| German literature, Topography subject = movement = influences = influenced =\n| signature = spouse = children = Alexander, Sebastian, Nick and Christian\n| website =\n}}\n\n'Nigel Hamilton' (born 16 February 1944) is an award-winning British-born\nbiographer, academic and broadcaster, whose works have been translated into\nsixteen languages. In the United States he is known primarily for his best-\nselling work on the young John F. Kennedy, JFK: Reckless Youth, which\nwas made into an ABC miniseries. In the United Kingdom, he is known for Monty, a\nthree-volume official life of Viscount Montgomery of Alamein, the World War II\nField Marshal which won both the 1981 Whitbread Award and the Templer Medal for\nMilitary History.\n\nHe has also written about the lives of Thomas Mann and former President Bill\nClinton as well as numerous other works in a variety of fields. His film on the\nlife of Field Marshal Montgomery won the New York Blue Ribbon Award for Best\nDocumentary. He founded the British Institute of Biography and became the first\nProfessor of Biography in the UK at De Montfort University. He is currently\nSenior Fellow at the John W. McCormack Graduate School of Policy Studies,\nUniversity of Massachusetts Boston, where he wrote a modern version of [[The\nTwelve Caesars]], titled American Caesars: Franklin D. Roosevelt to George W.\nBush, published in September 2010 by Yale University Press.\n","linknr":282,"url":"Nigel_Hamilton_(author)","recorded":1376420305,"links":["/w/index.php?t